column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: While boarding flight 149 JFK to GND. The FO and CA were waiting for refueling to be completed before doing the before start checked to the line. The F3, came in the cockpit and said there was a “medical issue” he then corrected and said ”safety issue in the jetway”. The CA was walking into the galley was told it was a bag fire in the jetway.  When he stepped into the jetway, he observed a wet bag, 2 empty water bottles, and fire extinguisher, next to an open bag.  It had a  blue battery disconnected from the bag. The F1 was watching over it with fire gloves. The CA then asked all in the jetway (starting to get crowded) if fire rescue was notified and was told ops knows about it. He immediately went into the cockpit and called ground operations to let them know they were had a bag fire in the jetway that appeared to be out. He also mentioned that he believed ops had informed Port authority but would confirm. He called OPS on the radio and they knew. He asked them to call the Port Authority to have the bag looked at. They said they would.  On his way back to the jetway he noticed all the customers were in their seats he checked on the bag. No fire and then made a PA to let the customers know all was safe and what had happened.  After things settled down it became clear to me what an amazing job the Flight attendants did. The F1 said she observed the customer walking down the jetway rolling a smoking bag. She stoped the customer prevented the bag from getting on the aircraft and called for safety team on the PA. She and the team went into action and by the time I got to the jetway, they had the fire out the battery cooled with water and the customers in their seats. Obviously the aircraft passageway was initially clogged with bags customers etc. that was cleared and the F3 got to the cockpit to let us know about the issue. I can’t say enough about how well the flight attendants did.   The suitcase was found to contain a medical refrigerator, manufactured by North Sciences.  The battery connected to the refrigerator was a 120 wH, Lithium Ion Battery.  It's only markings were as follows: Stirling Engine Li-ion Battery Model: JCB2405A Rated: 24V-5000mAh-120Wh Date: 2021-7 All other markings were in foreign language.  The bag also contained a Power Supply Unit, manufacturer unknown.  It had a Lithium Ion battery rated at 257.52 Wh.  It did not go into thermal runaway and did not contribute to the event.  Both items were confiscated and placed on internal reports DGR53-24 (battery) and DGR64-24 (Power Supply).
column169: The Inflight Crewmembers following the instructions in their manual and were able to resloved the situation quickly.  We are reviewing the incident to determine if a containment bag would have helped the situation further.

column168: On 01/04/2024, at 1336 hours, personnel at the CSX yard in Selkirk, New York, reported product leaking from inside the valve box of car LTCX 1902, a tank car loaded with Argon, refrigerated liquid.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Linde Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-0104-00121). David Scoons, a CSX Senior Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded to the incident and determined the cause of the release was a loose coupler fitting on a gauge panel feed line.  Response personnel tightened the loose coupler fitting and stopped the release.  The shipper’s representative, Timothy Lavallee (716-225-0242), was notified of the condition found and the corrective actions taken.

column168: On January 17, 2024, one (1) 50-pound bag of UN3262 was torn in transit and released approximately twenty-five (25) pounds of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the site. ER personnel utilized absorbents, hand tools, and a vacuum unit to remediate the powder-impacted trailer. All waste was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums staged at the terminal for future disposal.

WEARING FULL PPE AND FOLLOWING DECISION TREE, RESPONDER RESPONDED TO TRAILER, PLACED PACKAGE IN LINED SPILL TRAY AND RETURNED TO PROCESSING CENTER FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED THAT THE INTERNAL BOXES WERE MARKED WITH CORROSIVE PICTOGRAM. THE LABEL SAID THE PRODUCT CONTAINED PHOSPHORIC ACID. IT TESTED AS A 0 ON THE PH SCALE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OF ANY KIND ON THE OUTER BOX. UNDECLARED HAZMAT DISCOVERED. HMSC CONFIRMED. UNDECLARED PROTOCOL WAS FOLLOWED.

column168: The driver was traveling on I-71WB in KY when a passer by flagged him down. He then pulled off at the Sulfur Ky exit and inspected his load he noticed a frozen material at the back door of the trailer. The driver then grabbed some   absorbent to put down at the back of the trailer to prevent material from getting on the ground. The driver then called our emergency line at 1351ET to report the incident. The team was dispatched and arrived at 1745ET to start the clean up. The team dawned the proper PPE and proceeded to clean up the frozen material at the back of the trailer. There was aprxemetly 1-2oz that made it to the ground everything else was contained to  the trailer and absorbent wags. Once that was cleaned they opened the trailer and found material frozen on the floor and proceeded to clean it up. They then gained access to the drum that was about half way in the trailer and found that the bottom of the drum has approximately 1in crack at the bottom. The team put the damaged container into a salvage drum along with absorbents used to clean up the material. The team was able to finish the clean up around 0100ET.
column169: We believe that a nail from the pallet may have been the cause of the damage to the drum. We will be reviewing the use of pallets and to make sure they are in good condition with no nails sticking up as to catch the container and causing a puncture or rubbing a hole in it.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XCO experienced a UN3264 Kroff KR-B3020 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons of product released to an 8’ x 20’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Sodium bicarb and absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area to clean and neutralize the release. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were then collected and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into an 85-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Driver encountered deteriorating roadway conditions on his way to make delivery to the customer. At some point driver claims that a 3rd party driver veered into his lane causing him to take minor evasive action. This lead to loss of control when he contacted an icy road surface. The tanktruck rolled into the median where it came to rest. Ther was a rupture of a vapor valve as well as the diesel fuel tank. Luckily due to the cold weather only minor amounts of ammonia were lost through the vapor break. The police and local fire department were called to the scene to set up roadblocks and control the area.  The Huntsville, AL Hazmat team eventually made it to the site to assess the situation. It was deemed feasible to set the truck upright and tow away to a remote location for product offload and depressurization. Fugitive vapors were controlled by water application by the FD. A fuel cleanup team has been assigned to remove soil and diesel fuel as well.
column169: Rollover was due to unfortunate deterioration of conditions which is difficult to avoid. 3rd party may have played a role in the accident as well, but unfortunately there is lack of conclusive video evidence or an eyewitness to corroborate this. In future we will further promote the fact that our drivers have the last say when making a delivery as to whether it is safe or not without any repercussion. We need them to understand that no delivery is worth their own safety or the safety of the community.

column168: On January 18, 2024, at 0200 EST, an XPO Logistics tractor trailer hauling double trailers (truck # 05328716, trailer #s 03171129, 03171874) was involved in a rollover accident due to inclement weather conditions. Immediately after the accident occurred, the roads to the site were closed due to the weather and the unit was left onsite. No drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. On January 18, 2024, at 0256 EST, XPO Logistics contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage and oversee the above referenced incident. ERTS secured Haz-Mat Response Inc. (HMRI) to perform emergency response and remediation. On January 18, 2024, HMRI responded to the site at 1140 ET to obtain an assessment of the site. At the time, there was no visual release of material from the unit, but it was also in 5-6” of snow. Once HMRI left site, the wrecker unit showed up at approximately 1300 ET to haul the unit offsite. Initially they did not report seeing a release of material when the unit was up righted. On January 19th, HMRI mobilized to the wrecker yard to find the batteries had released approximately 50-100 gallons of battery acid to the trailer floor, walls, ceiling, and soil along the passenger side of the unit in the wrecker yard. An estimated 5-gallons of acid impacted a 26’ x 1’ area of the soil in the dirt lot. Soda ash and floor dry were deployed to the impacted trailer floor to neutralize the acid. The wrecker crew then advise to HMRI there was a loss of acid to the incident site in the soil median where the unit came to a rest. HMRI secured the unit at the wrecker’s yard and mobilized to the accident site where they confirmed an approximate 2-gallon release to a 5’ x 15’ area of the median ditch. The area was hand excavated and all impacted soil placed into a drum which was removed from site. At this point, the 7-gallons of material confirmed to impact soil/dirt was reported to the WY DEQ. On January 22, 2024, at 1100 ET, HMRI returned to the wrecker yard to complete trailer remediation. Each battery was wiped down and inspected. All 70 salvageable batteries were secured on the unit on 4 pallets to be hauled back to XPO with the unit. The trailer floor was neutralized with soda ash and floor dry, and the soil was hand excavated. A total of 213 damaged batteries were containerized into (9) 95-gallon poly drums and will attempt to be recycled. All impacted debris including the impacted floor dry, soda ash, soil, dirt, poly sheeting, cardboard, and PPE were collected and containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly and (3) 95-gallon poly drums for disposal. All waste is currently located at HMRI’s shop located in Windsor, CO pending profiling, disposal, and recycling. Please see attached photos (Appendix 2).

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XGR experienced a UN2491 Bonderite L-GP 505 Corrosion Inhibitor release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to an 8' x 10' area of the trailer floor and a 10' x 25' area of the asphalt dock as well as a catch basin. The release was due to a forklift puncture to the bottom of the drum. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were deployed to clean the impacted trailer floor and collected into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. A pressure washer and vac unit along with citric acid solution were then utilized to clean the impacted asphalt and catch basin. All impacted wastewater was placed into (7) 250-gallon poly totes. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On January 22, 2024, one (1) 500-pound cylinder of UN1009 was hissing when moved and covered in ice. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to inspect the cylinder and remediate the site. TLE personnel inspected the cylinder for any punctures or damage. No damage was found. Crews observed the cylinder was off gassing, creating a reaction. TLE personnel utilized hand tools, and absorbent pads, to remove ice from the frozen cylinder. Crews then moved the cylinder to the OS&D heat room, so the cylinder could gently warm up, and continue to release all of its contents. TLE personnel verified the cylinder released all of its contents and finished off gassing. Crews estimated 186 pounds of gas released. TLE personnel recommended the cylinder warm up a few hours before sending it for continued processing and shipping. All Ansul Halon 1301 (UN1009) impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 5-gallon pail and R+L personnel took possession of the waste to be added to the facility waste stream.

column168: On January 10, 2024, two (2) 275-gallon totes of UN1866 were crushed in transit and released approximately 300-gallons of product to the trailer interior and adjacent freight. HES personnel unloaded the trailer, wiping freight as it was being transferred out of the trailer. Crews then deployed absorbents to the paint thinner impacted trailer interior. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into 55-gallon drums for terminal disposal. HES transferred the remaining contents from the two (2) 275-gallon totes to one (1) new 275-gallon and two (2) 55-gallons drums. The damaged totes were cut into pieces and placed into two(55-gallon drums. HES removed seven (7) pallets that were damaged and/or impacted by the paint thinner. Additional damaged/impacted freight including aerosol cans of break cleaner and freon were removed and placed into 55-gallon drums for disposal. A total of 15 55-gallon drums of waste were generated and staged onsite for terminal disposal.

column168: This was the last pick up for the day and when the driver was doing his pick up the customer added more paint waste to the drum and he loaded it on his truck. The drive was about an hour back to the facility to unload for the end of the day. He arrive at approximately 1730 and when he opened the door to unload they noticed the drum was swelling up. The team at the facility emidiatly called for a team to come out and and address the container. The drum expanded to the point of failure at about 1830 before the team could arrive to address the situation. The bottom of the container failed and the contents was released into the truck with around 10 gallons making it to the pavement. They were able to contained it with absorbents and booms from spreading. The team arrived around 1930 to perform the clean up. They dawned the proper PPE and proceeded to clean up the material and overpacking the container to be shipped and disposed of properly. The crew was able to complete this around 2200.
column169: We believe that the paint waste that was added by the customer just before the driver picked up drum may have had an incompatible material in it which caused the reaction. The facility management team is working with the customer to figure out what was the added.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN2929 Sulfix 9272 Scavenger release from (2) 330-gallon poly totes. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 70-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 10’ area of the trailer floor and a 20’ x 20’ area of the asphalt lot below. The totes were punctured by metal sticking out from the trailer wall. Each tote was transferred into two new totes for shipment on. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly, (3) 55-gallon metal, and (3) 95-gallon poly drums. The two damaged totes were then cut up and containerized into (1) 95-gallon poly and (1) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: The box was found in the Damages Area wet and torn open.  It did not have any hazardous markings, so I thought it was water/rain from that day.  However, I felt a burning sensation on my wrists and discovered the liquid was battery acid.  It was an undeclared HazMat and a SDS was found to confirm its hazardous status. DescribePack: The FedEx Office box was torn open and soiled.  There were plastic bags of plastic Christmas ornaments spilling out (inner packing).  There were also three Non-HazMat items inside, but they got battery acid on them.  The battery was inside a plastic shopping bag. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: I found a SDS for the battery despite being sent Standard Domestic Residential and lacking any hazardous indications on the box.  I isolated the package and processed it after knowing it was hazardous.
